15/10/2004
SARAJEVO, Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) -- The commander of SFOR, Brigadier General Steven P. Schook, reiterated at a news conference Thursday (14 October) that the main responsibility for arresting war crimes suspects lies with BiH authorities and that NATO's role is only to assist in this process.
He also vowed that NATO's commitment to BiH would not be reduced after SFOR's mandate is completed at the end of December and military command is transferred to the EU.
In other news Thursday, SFOR troops searched the houses of two Serbs in Sokolac.
Mobile phones and documents were seized.
Also Thursday, German lawmaker Volker Ruehe visited Sarajevo and pledged German assistance in meeting the requirements for Euro-Atlantic integration.
He met with BiH Prime Minister Adnan Terzic and others.
(Dnevni avaz, Nezavisne novine - 15/10/04;
Fena, PBS BiH - 14/10/04)
